ěó2›                  CRJ 450 ››chapter 1  ›     The basic theme of chapter one was an introductory chapter that established the concept of community policing. It was divided into two parts. The first discussed what it is and the second said what it is not.›     As stated in the first section of chapter one, community policing is a dramatic change to traditional policing that incorporates a new philosophy that embodies that with the police working together with the public can they improve the qulity of the community. The police not only act as enforcers but advisors, counselors, good listeners and friends. Police are also supposed to broaden their narrow focus on crime to include new, creative solutions to a variety of community concerns that not only include crime, but the fear of it and also of neighborhood decay and disorder.›     In conclusion the concept of community policing involves a new philosophy in policing that incorporates the police department working together with the community in order to solve the underlying problems of the community which include crime and the fear of it, disorder and decay of the community. The officers goal is to establish a rappor and a sense of trust with the members of his community. He does this by patrolling a specific geographical area by foot rather than by patrol car. He wants to share his powers with the community. The goal is to let the members of his community to become the eyes and ears of the neighborhood. The members of the community are also encouraged to become volunteers both in time and goods to establish community programs to work together with its members and the police department that offer the promise of helping the community and reinforcing positive values.›     In addition to the officer becoming a common link between the community and the police department like that of an advisor or couselor and even a friend, the officer must become the problem solver of the community as well as the traditional crime fighter. He is asked to use his head in a new way, to think of a solution that underlies a series of events rather than to focus on each individual occurrence.›     The second part of the chapter stressed what community policing is not in order to reinforce what it is. It starts by saying that community policing is not a technique but rather a philosophy. It is not anti-technology nor is it soft on crime. Community policing is not out to act in the traditional hierarchy where the police department acts superior to the members of the community.›     Community policing is also not a substitute for social work or public relations but rather a compliment of these. Officers are encouraged to focus on solving community problems by using their time and efforts to address the concerns of the community. It is also not created to give special treatment to the upper crusts of society. It is designed to help those at all levels of society especially those in neighborhoods with high rates of crime. ›     The application of community policing is compared to that of regular policing is likened to that of the difference between emergency room doctors and that of the family physician. In the emergency room the doctor acts as a reactant to the crisis that occurs. He never knows what each emergency will bring. This is how the regular police offers responds to his job. He reacts to each emergency call not knowing what it will bring. On the othe hand the family physician abd the community patrol officer focus not only on the emergency needs of their "patients" but also on their long term care. Each establishes a relationship with their patients. The extra time spent between the doctor or cop and his patients allows each to know the concerns, habits and problems of their patients which will allow each to react better to any problems or concerns that may arrive.›     I found chapter one hard to criticize either positively or negatively since it was just an introductory chapter. However I did find that it did give good insight as to what community policing is and what it entails. 